## Article 1 — Purpose and Mission Statement

The OPRMT™ Framework Governance Charter establishes the definitive governing authority for all aspects of the OPRMT™ Prompt Engineering Systems framework. This Charter defines the structural, procedural, and enforcement standards that ensure the integrity, consistency, and commercial viability of the framework across all applications.

The mission of this Charter is to maintain a single canonical source of truth for all OPRMT™ specifications, to protect the intellectual property of the framework, and to enforce the quality and compliance standards that define the OPRMT™ brand in the marketplace.

**Core Objectives:**

- Define the authority structure governing all OPRMT™ outputs.
- Establish enforceable compliance standards for all library assets.
- Protect the commercial and intellectual integrity of the framework.
- Provide a traceable, auditable governance record for all changes.

---

## Article 2 — Scope of Application

This Charter applies universally and without exception to all OPRMT™ specifications, prompt libraries, certification programs, derivative systems, digital products, and any third-party implementations operating under the OPRMT™ brand or licensing structure.

Any system, product, or output that references, incorporates, or derives from OPRMT™ intellectual property is subject to the standards and enforcement protocols defined herein. No exemptions are granted without formal written approval from the governing authority.

**Scope Includes:**

- All five-component OPRMT™ framework specifications (OBJ, PAR, RES, MET, TLS).
- The DOAS™ scoring system and DCI™ formula.
- All prompt cluster libraries and digital product releases.
- The OPRMT™ Certification Program Engineering (CPE) infrastructure.
- All automation systems, APIs, and third-party integrations.
- Web properties, sales pages, and brand communications.

---

## Article 3 — Governing Authority and Leadership

The OPRMT™ Framework is governed exclusively by Michael W. Fleming, Founder and Lead Authority of OPRMT™ Prompt Engineering Systems. All decisions pertaining to framework architecture, standards enforcement, certification issuance, and intellectual property are reserved to the governing authority.

No modification to this Charter, the framework specifications, or any certified component may be enacted without the explicit approval of the governing authority. All contributors, licensees, and certified operators operate within the boundaries established by this office.

**Authority Responsibilities:**

- Sole authority over framework architecture and version approval.
- Final decision power over certification issuance and revocation.
- Exclusive authority to authorize derivative works or licensing agreements.
- Responsibility for the integrity and public representation of the OPRMT™ brand.

---

## Article 4 — Version Control and Change Management

All OPRMT™ specifications, libraries, and certified assets are subject to semantic versioning enforced under the format MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH. The canonical version source is the official GitHub repository maintained by the governing authority.

Every version increment must be accompanied by a structured change log documenting the rationale, scope of change, affected components, and approval status. No undocumented changes are permitted in any production-grade OPRMT™ asset.

**Versioning Protocol:**

- **MAJOR:** Breaking changes to framework architecture or compliance standards.
- **MINOR:** New components, prompts, or non-breaking feature additions.
- **PATCH:** Corrections, clarifications, and minor refinements.
- All version transitions require a documented change log entry.
- GitHub is the sole canonical source. Local copies are subordinate.

---

## Article 5 — Contribution Protocol

Contributions to the OPRMT™ framework are restricted to certified and formally approved contributors. No external submission may be incorporated into a production-grade OPRMT™ asset without passing through the defined validation workflow.

The validation workflow requires structural review against OPRMT™ component specifications, DOAS™ compliance scoring, PCE™ discipline validation, and explicit approval by the governing authority prior to any version increment or public release.

**Contribution Requirements:**

- Contributors must hold active OPRMT™ certification status.
- All submissions undergo DOAS™ compliance scoring prior to review.
- PCE™ discipline standards must be satisfied for all prompt assets.
- Governing authority approval is required before any production merge.
- Rejected submissions are documented with remediation requirements.

---

## Article 6 — Compliance and Quality Standards

All outputs produced under the OPRMT™ framework must meet the structural and quality standards defined in the current OPRMT™ Framework Specification and the DCS v2.0 compliance standard. Compliance is not optional and is enforced at every release gate.

The DOAS™ scoring system (Design Quality, Output Predictability, Architecture Compliance, System Efficiency) is the primary quality measurement instrument. All commercial-grade prompt assets must achieve a minimum DOAS™ threshold prior to release.

**Compliance Standards:**

- Full five-component structure (OBJ, PAR, RES, MET, TLS) is mandatory.
- DOAS™ scoring must meet minimum threshold for production release.
- DCS v2.0 compliance is required for all certified library assets.
- SHA-256 integrity hashing is applied to all versioned specifications.
- PCE™ validation is required for all prompt engineering outputs.

---

## Article 7 — Certification System

The OPRMT™ Certification Program Engineering (CPE) system governs the issuance, maintenance, and revocation of all OPRMT™ certifications. Certification is issued exclusively under the authority of Michael W. Fleming and is subject to strict integrity and anti-fraud protocols.

All certification assessments are evaluated against DOAS™ criteria using open-response AI grading. Session integrity is enforced through session tokens and anti-cheat architecture. Certification records are maintained in a Google Apps Script backend with full auditability.

**Certification Standards:**

- Certification is issued only upon passing all DOAS™ evaluation criteria.
- Anti-cheat architecture prevents unauthorized access or duplication.
- Session tokens are required for all certification assessment submissions.
- Revocation authority rests solely with the governing authority.
- All certification records are maintained with a full audit trail.

