## Article 8 — Intellectual Property and Proprietary Rights

The OPRMT™ framework, all associated trademarks, specifications, prompt libraries, scoring systems, and methodologies are the exclusive proprietary property of Michael W. Fleming. All rights are reserved.

No portion of the OPRMT™ framework may be reproduced, distributed, sublicensed, reverse-engineered, or incorporated into derivative works without explicit written authorization from the governing authority. Unauthorized use constitutes infringement and will be enforced.

**Proprietary Designations:**

- OPRMT™, DOAS™, PCE™, and DCI™ are proprietary designations.
- All prompt library assets are commercial intellectual property.
- Licensing agreements must be executed in writing prior to any authorized use.
- Derivative works require explicit written approval and attribution.
- Infringement is subject to enforcement under applicable law.

---

## Article 9 — Standardization and Documentation

The OPRMT™ framework is maintained through a structured documentation system anchored to the official GitHub repository. All specifications, component standards, and library assets are maintained in GitHub-compatible formats with full version history.

Official documentation includes the OPRMT™ Framework Specification (v1.0), the DCS v2.0 Technical Specification, all five component specifications (OBJ, PAR, RES, MET, TLS), and the PCE™ discipline specification. These documents constitute the canonical reference for all compliance determinations.

**Documentation Standards:**

- GitHub is the sole canonical source for all framework specifications.
- Documentation updates follow the version control protocol in Article 4.
- All component specifications are maintained as standalone reference documents.
- Public-facing documentation is reviewed prior to each release.

---

## Article 10 — Enforcement, Auditability, and Traceability

Governance enforcement ensures that all OPRMT™ assets, certifications, and derivative outputs maintain full auditability and traceability. Every production asset must carry a traceable version identifier, creation record, and compliance status.

Enforcement actions, including non-compliance findings, remediation requirements, and revocation decisions, are documented in the governance record and maintained by the governing authority. No undocumented enforcement action is recognized as valid.

**Enforcement Requirements:**

- Every production asset carries a unique Prompt ID and version identifier.
- Compliance status is recorded at each release gate.
- Non-compliance findings are documented with remediation requirements.
- Revocation decisions are recorded in the governance audit trail.
- SHA-256 hashing provides integrity verification for all specifications.

---

## Article 11 — Amendment Process

Amendments to this Charter require formal approval by the governing authority and must be documented as a version increment under the version control protocol established in Article 4. No informal or undocumented amendments are recognized as valid.

Proposed amendments must include a written rationale, a description of the affected sections, the proposed replacement language, and an effective date. All ratified amendments are incorporated into the next version release of this Charter.

**Amendment Protocol:**

- All amendments require explicit written approval from the governing authority.
- Amendments trigger a version increment under the semantic versioning protocol.
- Proposed amendments must document rationale and affected sections.
- Informal modifications to this Charter carry no legal or operational weight.

---

## Article 12 — Charter Status and Authority

This document, the OPRMT™ Framework Governance Charter Version 1.0, constitutes the official and binding governing authority for all matters within its stated scope. It supersedes all prior informal governance arrangements, verbal agreements, or earlier draft documents.

This Charter takes effect upon the date recorded herein and remains in force until formally superseded by a ratified subsequent version. Questions of interpretation are resolved exclusively by the governing authority.

